Japanese Finance Minister KiichiMiyazawa said the Group of Seven (G-7) countries reaffirmedtheir Paris accord on stabilising currencies to convince themarket of their resolve.    At a news conference after yesterday's G-7 meeting,Miyazawa said the ministers and central bank governors did notbelieve a totally new statement was needed. The speculativeselling did not reflect economic fundamentals, and since thefundamentals had not changed only a reaffirmation of the goalsof the Paris accord was needed, he said.    He said this test of the G-7 nations' resolve hadconcentrated on the yen, while other currencies, especially themark, had remained stable. Reuter&#3;